<p><a href="http://kompozer.net/">Kompozer HTML editor</a> is one of my
most used applications. Not really for editing web pages but as my
default document editor. What's better than an standardized document
format (<a href="http://www.w3.org/TR/xhtml1/">XHTML</a>) with WYSIWYG
features (<a href="http://www.w3.org/TR/CSS/">CSS</a>) and fully web
compatible? Nothing, in my honest opinion. That's why I've developed
throught all this years <a
href="http://olea.org/estilo-web/estilo-comun.css">my own default CSS
style</a> focused on almost 100% pure HTML document structure.</p>
<p>As you maybe know Kompozer is the un-official update of <a
href="http://nvu.com/">Nvu</a> which is sadly stopped. For some time
its development seemed stopped too. But a few days ago I discovered <a href="http://kazhack.org/?tag/editor">it
is again ongoing</a>. I have done some test and figured out a <a
href="http://kompozer.svn.sourceforge.net/viewvc/kompozer/trunk/mozilla/composer/config/mozconfig.fedora?view=log">configuration
for building in Fedora</a> without apparent problems.</p>

<p>So my next natural step is to try to build into RPM. This is <a
href="http://olea.org/tmp/kompozer.spec">done now</a>. You can
directly download the <a
href="http://olea.org/paquetes-rpm/fedora-10/kompozer-0.8a3-2.fc10.i386.rpm">binary
package</a> and the <a
href="http://olea.org/paquetes-rpm/fedora-10/kompozer-0.8a3-2.fc10.src.rpm">sources</a>
or you can install through <a
href="http://olea.org/paquetes-rpm/olea-repo-release-0.0.3-1olea.noarch.rpm">my
RPM repository</a>. Warning: this is alpha software and alpha
packaging. Expect updates and contribute bugs and suggestions.</p>

<p>Hopefuly, when finished, I'll postulate this for being held in the
main <a href="http://fedoraproject.org/">Fedora distro</a>.</p>

<p>Thanks to all the people responsable of the Kompozer/Nvu development!</p>


<p><span style="font-weight: bold;">PD:</span> I've updated the
packaging, now the links point to release 2. Enjoy!</span></p>
